
.1 Getting started with gawk

.1.1 What is gawk?

gawk is the gnu version of the UNIX awk, another stream editor.
it searches fules for patterns of text and performs special actions when theres a match.

since programs in awk are "data-driven" you only have to describe the data you want the program to work with and what to do when it finds it

.1.2 Gawk commands

when you run awk you specify an awk program that tells awk what to do, these are series of rules that specify the pattern to search and the action to perform.
you can run a short awk program from the command line like:
	awk PROGRAM inputfile(s)
or if you gotta do multiple changes, you should put it on a script like:
	awk -f PROGRAM-FILE inputfile(s)

.2 The print program

.2.1 Printing selected fields

when reading, awk splits lines into fields using IF (field separators, different from bash IFS but do the same). the variables $1, $2, ..., $n hold the values to the n-th field
the awk print command allows us to print this fields of specified input, so by doing
	ls -l | awk '{ print $9 $5 }'
we would print the field 9 and 5 of EVERY line of the output of ls -l

you can add tabs and strings on the awk command to make it look better like
	ls -l | awk '{ print "frsjio" $9 "\t" $5}'

.2.3 The print command and regular expressions

a regular expression can be used as a pattern by enclosing it in '/', and the syntax would be:
	awk 'EXPRESSION {PROGRAM}' file(s)
for example
	df -h | awk '/dev\/hd/ { print $6 "\t" $5 }'
prints the 6 and 5 field of the lines matching the pattern dev/hd

.2.4 Special patterns

to print something before the main command, you can use the BEGIN statement like:
	ls -l | awk 'BEGIN { print "Files:\n" } { print $9 }'
or the END statement to insert texet after the input is processed

.3 Gawk variables

.3.1 The input field separator
the field separator, which is a char or a regex, is a delimiter to for awk to split lines. it is represented by the IF built-in var
you can change the value when running an awk program with the BEGIN statement like:
	awk 'BEGIN { FS=":" } { print $1 $2 }' /text.txt

.3.2 The output separators
by putting commas to separate the arguments on the print command, they are printed with spaces between them, and just like with IF you can change OFS on the BEGIN statement

also, for every time awk prints somethin from a print command, it outputs a stringcalled output record separator or ORS which can also be changed like ORS and FS

and there is a NR built-in var that holds the number of records processed, incremented afer reading a new input line

.3.4 User define variables
you can define your own variables with awk by using the = operator
